### Compare the time it takes for the count query
Comparison between same counting queries using Hive
- As observed below (the counting queries), the second counting query takes less time. This is because the system hold the cache in the memory. When the data is used frequently, the miss rate will be decreased and hence it will take less time.

Comparison between counting query and the bash command

## Performance Optimization
### Select Query Test

In the following blocks, it will find Canada's GDP growth as annual percentage in 2015. It will check all the indicator_name to find the indicator_code that represent the annual GDP growth percentage. Then, it will find Canada's GDP annual percentage growth in 2015.
As notcied in the following blocks, it takes a very long time(71s) to select the row(s) which fit a certain criteria(even longer than the count query(56s)). This is because it needs to iterate through the table to find the row that fits those criteria which is more than log(n) operation(as there will 3 iteration in total for indicator_code, year, and countryName).
To solve it, both partitioning and columnaring can be used and it is implemented in the following sections.

### New Performance
With the columnar optimization described above, the performance is increased. Blocks below is a test of the queries performance. The first query will compute maximum annual GDP growth of each country and then print out the maximum value, year that it occurred, the the country name. The second query will simple print annual GDP growth for each country ordered by country name and then the year.

Although the performance of hive query is maxmized, it is still slower than spark query. This is becasue spark will save the intermediate data in the memory instead of save the intermediate result in disk like Hive does.
